AGI - It's about 8.30 when the land returns to tremble in the Flegrei Fields. The magnitude index scores a 3.4, updated after 3.6. We are not at the 4.4 levels on Monday night, but enough to rekindle fear. In Pozzuoli there are those who prepare to go out and who is already at work. David is taking a coffee in the port area and he realizes the bar dancing. The bartender does not bend and continues his chores as if nothing were. His colleague, on the other hand, immediately departs from the register and reaches the exit of the premises. Outside, on the benches of the square, some elderly look without saying anything, staying still for a few seconds, as if time had stopped. A few meters away are the curtains mounted by the Civil Protection to accommodate some thirty people who, by choice, decided to leave their home last night to feel more calm. For those who were still asleep, the shock sounds a little like an alarm clock that brings them back to reality. He also lives here the president of the Order of Psychologists of Campania, who on Monday evening, after the strongest shock, left home with his wife, children and cat.
&nbsp;
"In front of this type of phenomena - explains to AGI Armando Cozzuto - being afraid is normal. It represents a healthy reaction when we face a real danger." Psychologists specializing in emergency intervention were alerted on Monday in late evening, because "it is important to intervene promptly in the face of this type of phenomena to immediately provide a first form of containment - it emphasizes - through specific protocols aimed at avoiding the emergence of disorders, such as post-traumatic stress." Those who live in these areas, have long lived with the effects of bradisism and a little is used to it, but the last seismic events have made the climate of tension and apprehension grow. Particularly delicate is the situation of the little ones.
&nbsp;
"We record forms of reactive discomfort that must be contained - the president of Campanian psychologists emphasizes - such as sleeping disorders, enures and separation anguish when they have to go to school." It is important that parents "tell them the truth - warns Cozzuto - without denying what is happening and making their children understand that there are them to manage the situation".
&nbsp;
Someone coined nicknames to personify the phenomenon of bradisism. "We call it 'mister Bread'," says Cozzuto. The impression is that, at times like these, everything can be used to lead to a normality that perhaps has never really been there and that, in the last few hours, it seems even further away.

